Description of Assignment


Today, I will be discussing my attempts to replicate “The role of nocturnal omnivorous lemurs as seed dispersers in Malagasy rain forests” by Ramananjato et al. published in biotropica in 2020. First though, I would like to mention that I had meant to discuss another study with you all today. This paper, “Crop Feeding by Brown Howlers (Alouatta guariba clamitans) in Forest Fragments: The Conservation Value of Cultivated Species” by Oscar Chaves and Julio Cesar Bicca-Marques, proved difficult to replicate for a variety of reasons. The study was the analysis of the fruits howler monkeys ate of different species in three different orchards. However, the data set did not include the basal area of each species within each orchard making it impossible to calculate the fruit avalibility index of each species. Secondly, a link in the study to the market value of each fruit species was no longer operational. This made it impossible to calculate the economic value of the fruit which was lost due to the crop feeding.


So, I moved on to the next paper anticipating less problems. The paper Ramananjato et al. 2020 analyzes the role of two species of mouse lemur, Microcebus rufus and Microcebus jollyae, in seed dispersal in Madagascar’s forest. The researchers collected seeds, some which had been defecated by mouse lemurs and others which had been extracted from fresh fruits and subjected them to various growth experiments. For Microcebus rufus, one experiment looked at seed growth in a petri dish setting and the other looked at seed growth on the forest ground. For Microcebus jollyae, experiments were conducted in a petri dish, in a semi-shaded plot and a shaded plot. From these experiments, the researchers compared germination rate, germination time and seedling length after a certain period of time between defecated and control seeds using mixed effect models and survival analysis.

Ramananjato et al. 2020

Introduction

The authors begin with a discussion of seed dispersal as an important ecological process. Seed dispersal is implicated in forest regeneration and plant community maintianance both important for the continued existence of forest and their biodiversity. The authors point out that while the role of large diurnal herbivores in seed dispersal is commonly studied, the role of small nocturnal omnivores is also important ecologically. In fact, since the foraging behavior of omnivores is different from frugivores (ex. traveling further) it might be important in a different way. So even if most of the seed dispersal is done by large herbivores, the small contributions made by omnivores may have an outsized effect.

Firstly, I am glad the authors discuss extensivly the importance of seed dispersal. It is foundational in ecology and should be paid more attention to in primatology. I am also happy that the I also appreciate the author’s attention to the novelty of this study. It is no secret in primatology that small bodied and nocturnal primates are studied much less than large bodied diurnal ones. I agree that studying small bodied and nocturnal primate seed dispersal is important. I also found the argument that the omnivorous foraging behavior compelling and worth investiagation.

Methods

The mouse lemurs were studied in two sites, Ranomafana National Park which is more prestine and Kianjavato Classified Forest which is fragmented and degraded. Two species, Microcebus rufus and Microcebus jollyae were studied in the two sites. Most of the M. rufus population was found in Ranomafana National Park while most of the M jollyae forest was found in Kianjavato Classified Forest. To collect the seeds, the researchers set up transects and set traps to capture mouse lemurs. Researches then returned to the traps and hoped to find a mouse lemur who had defecated. Assuming one was found, they were released and the the feces was collected.

After collection seeds were identified and subjected to various growth experiments. For Microcebus rufus, one experiment looked at seed growth in a petri dish setting and the other looked at seed growth on the forest ground. For Microcebus jollyae, experiments were conducted in a petri dish, in a semi-shaded plot and a shaded plot. From these experiments, the researchers compared germination rate, germination time and seedling length after a certain period of time between defecated and control seeds using mixed effect models and survival analysis.

I think an interesting comparison would have been between the two sites because one was a fragmented forest and one was a intact. Unfortunatly this was probably not possible because of the different species make-up of the forest. Also, it is possible this experiment could have been done non-invasively by following mouse lemurs until they defecated. Although, this is complicated by their small bodies and their nocturnal behavior.

Results

Of the seeds which the mouse lemurs dispersed, 17% were non-native species. The researchers found significance for some of the growth parameters in some of the experiments but not all of them. I will discuss these results below in the replication.

Discussion

The discussion again emphasizes the importance of seed dispersal and recognizes that some species which are dispersed by mouse lemurs are seen in the literature to be dispersed by other species of primates and birds yet other plant species are not known to be dispersed by any other animals in the area. The results in their paper are consistent with larger findings in the literature that digestion through animals assist in seed germination compared to control seeds, but they critize themselves by stating that their sample size for control seeds was low compared to defecated ones. The authors discuss how seed dispersal of non-native plants has been shown to assist in invasive species invasion of tropical forest. Concerningly, they point to one plant, soap bush (Clidemia hirta) which is dispersed by Microcebus jollyae has been shown to be invasive in the literature. Given the sucessful results of the semi-shaded plot experiment and M. jollyae’s inhabitance of a fragmented and degraded forest, … not done yet …

Survival analysis table

Now, I will construct a table with the replication values alongside the original values

Legend for table construction object:

Species: r = Microcebus rufus, j = Microcebus jollyae

Experiment: p = Petri dish, f = Forest ground, s = semi-shaded plot, c = shaded plot

Study: rep = replication, og = original

Model: n = Number of observations l = Seedling length, t = Germination time, r = germination rate, sur = survival analysis

r_p_rep_sur <- c("X^2 = 41.38", "df = 1", "p = 1e-10")
r_p_og_sur <- c("X^2 = 20.62", "df = 1", "p < .0001")

r_f_rep_sur <- c("X^2 = NA", "df = NA", "p = NA")
r_f_og_sur <- c("X^2 = NA", "df = NA", "p = NA")

j_p_rep_sur <- c("X^2 = 0.02", "df = 1","p = 0.9")
j_p_og_sur <- c("X^2 = 66.08", "df = 1", "p = .96")

j_s_rep_sur <- c("X^2 = 1.4", "df = 1", "p = 0.2")
j_s_og_sur <- c("X^2 = 1.60", "df = 1", "p = .20")

j_c_rep_sur <- c("X^2 = 0.17", "df = 1", "p = .7")
j_c_og_sur <- c("X2 = 0.30", "df = 1", "p = .56")

t1_sur <- cbind(r_p_rep_sur, r_p_og_sur, r_f_rep_sur, r_f_og_sur, j_p_rep_sur, j_p_og_sur,
                j_s_rep_sur, j_s_og_sur, j_c_rep_sur, j_c_og_sur)
t2_sur <- as.data.frame(t1_sur)
t3_sur <- t2_sur %>% gt() %>%
  cols_label(r_p_rep_sur = "Petri dish experiment replication values",
             r_p_og_sur = "Petri dish experiment original values", 
             r_f_rep_sur = "Forest ground experiment replication values",
             r_f_og_sur = "Forest ground experiment original values",
             j_p_rep_sur = "Petri dish experiment replication values",
             j_p_og_sur = "Petri dish experiment original values",
             j_s_rep_sur = "Semi-shaded plot experiment replication values",
             j_s_og_sur = "Semi-shaded plot experiment original values",
             j_c_rep_sur = "Shaded plot experiment replication values",
             j_c_og_sur = "Shaded plot experiment original values") %>% 
  tab_header(title = md("Summary table of the Cox model with frailty")) %>%
  tab_spanner(label = "Microcebus rufus", columns = c(r_p_rep_sur, r_p_og_sur, r_f_rep_sur, r_f_og_sur)) %>%
  tab_spanner(label = "Microcebus Jollyae", columns = c(j_p_rep_sur, j_p_og_sur,
                                            j_s_rep_sur, j_s_og_sur, j_c_rep_sur, j_c_og_sur))
